    <h1>6.2.1 Functional Analysis: Two Factor Authentication</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h2 id=3D"id-6.2.1FunctionalAnalysis:TwoFactorAuthentication-Introd=
uction">Introduction</h2>
<p>As a result of the Toreon security audit, a need for two factor authenti=
cation for prilvileged (administrator) users became clear. Two factor authe=
ntication is a security mechanism where a user needs not only something he =
knows (ie his username &amp; password), but also something he has (ie his p=
hone) to log on.&nbsp;</p>
<p>By requiring this second factor, we can substantially increase security.=
&nbsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"id-6.2.1FunctionalAnalysis:TwoFactorAuthentication-Typesofsecondf=
actor">Types of second factor</h2>
<p>Several ways of providing the second factor in a 2FA authentication sche=
me exist:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>Send users an email containing a secret code they'll fill in on the web=
site.&nbsp;<br><br>Advantages:<br>&nbsp;- Free<br>&nbsp;- Nothing to carry<=
br>Disadvantages:<br>&nbsp;- When email is compromised, the website is also=
 compromised<br>&nbsp;- Would be time consuming for the user</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>Send users an sms containing a secret code they'll fill in on the websi=
te<br><br>Advantages:<br>&nbsp;- Easy for users<br>Disadvantages:<br>&nbsp;=
- Not free<br>&nbsp;- Susceptible to telephony provider attack</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>Have users use a dedicated app (ie google authenticator)<br><br>Advanta=
ges:<br>&nbsp;- Free<br>&nbsp;- Relatively easy<br>&nbsp;- More secure than=
 email &amp; sms&nbsp;<br>Disadvantages:<br>&nbsp;- Few? A little more work=
 maybe than sms</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>Use a dedicated hardware token (ie FIDO)<br><br>Advantages:<br>&nbsp;- =
Most secure<br>&nbsp;- Easy<br>Disadvantages:<br>&nbsp;- Difficult/impossib=
le to automate for testing (anyone want to build a robot arm to press the l=
ittle button on the top of the device?)&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;- Not free: need a d=
evice per administrator. These are not that expensive but still somewhat an=
noying<br>&nbsp;- If we ever want to expand the 2FA to non-administrator us=
ers (perhaps opt-in), users will not have these tokens and will need to pur=
chase them<br>&nbsp;- At the moment, pretty much no support for mobile (cel=
l phone). A scenario where an admin needs to look up something quickly on h=
is phone is not that far fetched, and would be made impossible by this (no =
way to connect, no drivers, no android integration, ...)&nbsp;</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<p>Author's recommendation: use a dedicated app</p>
<p><br></p>
<h2 id=3D"id-6.2.1FunctionalAnalysis:TwoFactorAuthentication-Userinterface"=
>User interface</h2>
<p>When logging in, users are shown the very same username &amp; password s=
creen. When their provided credentials are correct, they're shown another p=
age where they are asked for their code.&nbsp;</p>
<p> </p>
<div style=3D"width: 100.0%;height: 100.0%;text-align: center;">
<img alt=3D"Balsamiq Wireframes" style=3D"max-width: 600.0px;" src=3D"https=
://nexchargeapplications.atlassian.net/wiki/download/attachments/549748791/=
balsamiq_E1E7C231-AFE0-4F54-AAFE-5E4A97F16BCA_Master.png">
</div>=20
<p></p>
<p>In the user profile, we will add a link that is visible only to administ=
rators reading "Set 2 Factor Authentication code". Loading this page will g=
enerate a new server-side code, set it in the database for your user and wi=
ll show you the code you need to configure your 2FA app. It will also show =
a QR code that can be <span class=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-ref=3D"c77=
f4b69-9954-4e40-905c-f7b7d3356441">used for quicker configuration</span>.&n=
bsp;</p>
<p> </p>
<div style=3D"width: 100.0%;height: 100.0%;text-align: center;">
<img alt=3D"Balsamiq Wireframes" style=3D"max-width: 600.0px;" src=3D"https=
://nexchargeapplications.atlassian.net/wiki/download/attachments/549748791/=
balsamiq_2278E287-509B-183B-1098-2EC38DDDB7D8_Master.png">
</div>=20
<p></p>
<h2 id=3D"id-6.2.1FunctionalAnalysis:TwoFactorAuthentication-Recovery">Reco=
very</h2>
<p>If a user were to lose access to the key-generating app, he can contact =
another administrator. The administrator with functioning access will imper=
sonate the user who lost his token and will communicate the iniitial setup =
code to him.&nbsp;</p>
<p>If this too fails, the administrator can use database queries to restore=
.&nbsp;</p>
<p><br></p>
<h2 id=3D"id-6.2.1FunctionalAnalysis:TwoFactorAuthentication-Impactontestin=
g">Impact on testing</h2>
<p>Currently, some of our tests depend on the test user having administrato=
r permissions. These tests test if the administrator part of the website is=
 functioning normally.&nbsp;</p>
<p>If the account used for testing requires administrator permissions, we n=
aturally need to provide a way for the automated tests to "read" a new veri=
fication code.&nbsp;</p>
<p>There are several options to solve this issue:</p>
<p>&nbsp;1) Stop testing the administrator part of the website. Currently t=
he tests for the administrator part of the website are very limited and hon=
estly would not be greatly missed. A middle road would be to only run these=
 admin tests on the master branch &amp; not require 2FA for&nbsp;<a class=
=3D"external-link" href=3D"mailto:test@test.com" rel=3D"nofollow">test@test=
.com</a>&nbsp;on master.&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;2) Hardcode the security token for&nbsp;<a class=3D"external-link"=
 href=3D"mailto:test@test.com" rel=3D"nofollow">test@test.com</a>&nbsp;into=
 the smoketest test project. Include the code to generate 2FA verification =
codes based on this token into the smoketests program. This is in itself a =
security risk&nbsp;=E2=80=93 anyone gains access to our source code would i=
mmediately gain access to the production environment (note that this is cur=
rently also the case, due to&nbsp;<a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"mailto=
:test@test.com" rel=3D"nofollow">test@test.com</a>&nbsp;having admin permis=
sions).&nbsp;</p>
<p><span class=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-ref=3D"239c2147-adb1-45c9-8c1=
1-39694df7928f">3) Install a separate key-generating application onto the b=
uild server and have the smoketest code use that to read smoke tests. This =
would mean that anyone with access to the development server can also gain =
access to the production server, but that is already the case (they could d=
eploy a new version of the software...).</span>&nbsp;</p>
<p><br></p>
